the latest
installment in our series of
essays.

49:51.822 --> 49:57.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tom Nichols, author of the book
"The Death
of Expertise," shares his Humble
Opinion on

49:57.260 --> 49:59.162 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the demise of experts.

49:59.196 --> 50:03.834 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TOM NICHOLS, Author, "The Death
of Expertise":
A few years ago, a mischievous
group of pollsters

50:03.867 --> 50:07.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
asked American voters whether
they would support
bombing the country of Agrabah.

50:07.571 --> 50:12.743 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As you might expect, Republicans
tended to
support military action, while
Democrats were

50:12.776 --> 50:13.844 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
more reluctant.

50:13.877 --> 50:17.614 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's only one problem:
Agrabah doesn't
exist.

50:17.647 --> 50:19.783 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's from the animated Disney
film "Aladdin."

50:19.816 --> 50:24.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Only about half the people
surveyed figured
this out, and liberals and
conservatives gleefully

50:24.788 --> 50:26.990 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
pointed fingers at each other.

50:27.024 --> 50:31.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For experts in foreign affairs,
however, there
was no way around the alarming
reality that

50:31.795 --> 50:37.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
so many Americans had a
well-defined view
on bombing a cartoon.

50:37.401 --> 50:38.935 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm one of those experts.

50:38.969 --> 50:42.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I teach both civilians and
military officers
about national security affairs.

50:42.672 --> 50:48.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In my career, I have advised the
Pentagon,
the CIA, and political leaders
from both major

50:48.178 --> 50:49.479 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
parties.

50:49.513 --> 50:52.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Increasingly, however, laypeople
don't care
about expert views.

50:52.682 --> 50:58.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead, many Americans have
become insufferable
know-it-alls, locked in constant
conflict

50:58.355 --> 51:02.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with each other, while knowing
almost nothing
about the subject they are
debating.

51:03.026 --> 51:04.928 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How did this happen?

51:04.961 --> 51:10.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How is it that people now not
only doubt expert
advice, but believe themselves
to be as smart,

51:10.267 --> 51:14.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
or even smarter, than
experienced professionals?

51:14.204 --> 51:18.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Parents who refuse to vaccinate
a child, for
example, aren't really
questioning their doctors.

51:19.009 --> 51:20.944 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're replacing their doctors.

51:20.977 --> 51:25.315 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have decided that attending
the university
of Google, as one anti-vaccine
activist put

51:25.348 --> 51:28.285 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it, is the same as going to
medical school.

51:28.318 --> 51:32.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People who have no idea how much
the United
States spends on foreign aid
think that they're

51:32.589 --> 51:35.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the peers of experienced
diplomats.

51:35.692 --> 51:38.628 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Experts in almost every field
can tell similar
stories.

51:38.662 --> 51:40.764 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's a lot of blame to go
around for all
of this.

51:40.797 --> 51:44.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The smartphones and tablets that
we carry
around all day that we think can
answer anything

51:44.701 --> 51:46.736 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are only part of the problem.

51:46.770 --> 51:51.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The American educational system,
from grade
school to graduate school,
encourages students

51:51.475 --> 51:53.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to think of themselves and their
views as
special.

51:53.977 --> 51:56.580 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
An A is now a common grade.

51:56.613 --> 52:01.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The news media, while trying to
tell people
what they need to hear, must
compete for ears,

52:01.184 --> 52:06.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
eyes, and clicks, and so are
also forced to
ask them what they'd like to
hear.

52:06.823 --> 52:11.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And even if we manage to avoid
the intellectual
saboteurs of the Internet, we're
still all

52:11.528 --> 52:16.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
too likely to get our news and
views from
social media, where a silly meme
from your

52:16.399 --> 52:22.272 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
aunt Rose in Schenectady
competes for your
attention with actual
information.

52:22.305 --> 52:26.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We need to find our way back
from this ego-driven
wilderness.

52:26.109 --> 52:30.847 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Historically, people return to
valuing expert
views in times of trouble or
distress.

52:30.881 --> 52:35.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're all willing to argue with
our doctors
until our fever is out of
control.

52:35.752 --> 52:37.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Let's hope it doesn't come to
that.

52:37.521 --> 52:39.356 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But that's where we're headed.

52:39.389 --> 52:43.527 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And unless we start accepting
the limitations
of our own knowledge, then each
of us is failing

52:43.560 --> 52:49.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
